The first symbol of the string is the terminal ‘t4’.  
In the grammar this terminal is produced only by the non-terminal NT41:

 NT41 → 't4'

Consequently, in any derivation of the whole string the left-most leaf of the parse tree must be the production NT41 → ‘t4’.  
Moving one level up, NT41 can appear as the left child of a binary rule only in the following productions:

 NT17 → NT41 NT43  
 NT26 → NT41 NT69  
 NT20 → NT41 NT24

Therefore, in every possible parse the token that comes immediately after ‘t4’ must be the first token generated by NT43, NT69 or NT24 respectively.

• NT43 can begin a derivation only through  
 NT43 → NT2 NT18 or NT43 → NT42 NT73.  
The first token produced by NT2 is one of {t69, t100, t102}, and the first token produced by NT42 is either t9 or t63.  
None of these is ‘t31’.

• NT69 can produce the terminals t3 or t15 or t36 (and nothing else as an initial token).  
Again, none of these is ‘t31’.

• NT24 starts with NT5 or NT73 (rules NT24 → NT5 NT19 and NT24 → NT73 NT53).  
NT5 can begin only with t24 or t40, while NT73 can begin only with t70 – never with ‘t31’.

Hence, no derivation whose first token is ‘t4’ can yield ‘t31’ as the very next token.  
Since the given string starts with the pair “t4 t31”, it cannot be generated by the grammar.

For the start symbol S the grammar offers exactly four binary productions:

1. S → NT14 NT8  
2. S → NT43 NT15  
3. S → NT21 NT13  
4. S → NT67 NT6  

In any derivation, the yield of the first righthand non-terminal forms the left part of the string, and the yield of the second non-terminal forms the right part (including the final token).  
Our string ends with the token t75, so whichever of the four rules is used, the **second** non-terminal (NT8, NT15, NT13 or NT6) must be able to generate a string whose last symbol is t75.

Let us inspect these four candidates.

• NT8  
  – Terminal rules: NT8 → 't79' | 't3'  
  – Binary rule: NT8 → NT46 NT77  
  Neither NT46 nor NT77 (nor any of their descendants) has a terminal rule for t75.  
  ⇒ NT8 can never produce t75.

• NT15  
  – Terminal rules: NT15 → 't19' | 't6' | 't51' | 't93' | 't87'  
  – Binary rule: NT15 → NT40 NT25  
  NT40 has no t75-rule, and NT25 expands only to  
        NT29 NT48 | NT57 NT78 | NT40 NT67 | NT23 NT46,  
  none of which (nor their descendants) can yield t75.  
  ⇒ NT15 can never produce t75.

• NT13  
  – Terminal rule: NT13 → 't7'  
  – Binary rules: NT13 → NT2 NT62 | NT50 NT10 | NT16 NT40  
  Each rightmost partner (NT62, NT10, NT40) ultimately expands to terminals other than t75.  
  ⇒ NT13 can never produce t75.

• NT6  
  – Terminal rules: NT6 → 't11' | 't47' | 't27'  
  – Binary rules:  
        NT6 → NT68 NT48  
        NT6 → NT71 NT3  
        NT6 → NT21 NT13  
        NT6 → NT79 NT59  
  The rightmost symbols here are NT48, NT3, NT13 and NT59.  
  None of NT48, NT3, NT13 or NT59 (nor their descendants) has a terminal rule for t75.  
  ⇒ NT6 can never produce t75.

Since none of the four possible second non-terminals can generate a string ending in t75, **no derivation from S can produce any string whose last token is t75**.  
Our target string ends with t75, so it is not in the language.
